      },
      "date": "2014-05-06 02:27:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified-1\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/698dd4c0-d4c3-11e3-bdb0-52540035b04c).  Ran 15 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity-lfsck.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3561978c4eb5ef2559a58a4e3345573e566a54c9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-06 08:15:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nJinshan, I'm curious why ll_write_end() doesn't unlock page? Basically this doesn't conform to kernel locking policy, so if we call kernel function in IO path this may cause deadlock in other corner cases like this.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "287e110d0465e1dcf115cb5aab17df58e8aedc31",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-05-06 08:35:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/86379a2a-d4f5-11e3-b520-52540035b04c).  Ran 21 tests.  1 tests failed: lustre-rsync-test.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "254911e567a612b4bcc71b58ef624e8aa9778c4d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-05-06 16:10:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n\"Jinshan, I'm curious why ll_write_end() doesn't unlock page? Basically this doesn't conform to kernel locking policy, so if we call kernel function in IO path this may cause deadlock in other corner cases like this.\"\n\nWe can unlock the page after it has been added into dirty cache on the OSC layer. For performance reason, we don't want to add the dirty pages into cache by page basis, so we hold them back until the current file IO is complete, or exception occurs.\n\nYes, there are lots of corner cases, and fortunately they're solvable so far ;-)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "63c478ffab6e555097114934381bd345d4c41733",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-07 07:11:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nBut why CPS_OWNED state needs taking page lock? And we still call lock/unlock_page() in many places directly, if we can call them in all places, is there a chance we separate page lock state with CPS_OWNED state?\n\nBTW to avoiding deadlock in the long run, we need to track kernel changes in IO functions, which doesn't look to be decent.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6fa99cf5381e89177ed17a2e65a041cb35037ac4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-05-07 08:45:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n\"For performance reason, we don't want to add the dirty pages into cache by page basis\"\n\nJingshan, could you explain it more? I think there could be other solutions rather than keeping page locked in write_end().",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "bffe3369e15c5b08a617d096fc1a16ea6acf4d97",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
