    {
      "id": "4ea220b53c58b702efd4989046212ebb11a3ec61",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-05-09 04:49:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n\"But why CPS_OWNED state needs taking page lock? And we still call lock/unlock_page() in many places directly, if we can call them in all places, is there a chance we separate page lock state with CPS_OWNED state?\"\n\nCPS_OWNED is a private state for cl_page to hold a page exclusively. It's natural to use linux kernel page lock for this purpose. We only {lock,unlock}_page at LLITE layer.\n\n\"BTW to avoiding deadlock in the long run, we need to track kernel changes in IO functions, which doesn't look to be decent.\"\n\nIsn't it a regular work to track the kernel changes as a file system developer ;-)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7741e2b4b347ad28b21905c5ce0604fb5ea92715",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-05-09 04:52:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n\"Jingshan, could you explain it more? I think there could be other solutions rather than keeping page locked in write_end().\"\n\nWe group pages in a private commit queue and submit the pages to OSC layer in batch.\n\nPlease let me know your solution to not keep the page locked after write_end().",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
